Synopsis

This document is a demonstration of a Company in the process of investigating its public image. The Twitter sentiment investigation within this document identifies Social Media content, expressing what the public associated with the name of the Company.

1) General Twitter Sentiment

# General Twitter content
twitter <- readLines("en_US.twitter.txt", encoding="UTF-8")

# Function to clean the general twitter text
textOptimal <- function(corpus){
  cleanText <- removePunctuation(corpus)
  cleanText <- removeNumbers(cleanText)
  cleanText <- str_replace_all(cleanText, "[^[:alnum:]]", " ")
  cleanText <- stripWhitespace(cleanText)
  cleanText <- tolower(cleanText)
  return(cleanText)}

# Sample of 1000 General Tweets
twitterOptimal <- textOptimal(twitter[1:1000])

Five lines of General Twitter Sentiment:

# Example of a General Tweet
twitterOptimal[1:5]
## [1] "how are you btw thanks for the rt you gonna be in dc anytime soon love to see you been way way too long" 
## [2] "when you meet someone special youll know your heart will beat more rapidly and youll smile for no reason"
## [3] "theyve decided its more fun if i dont"                                                                   
## [4] "so tired d played lazer tag ran a lot d ughh going to sleep like in minutes "                            
## [5] "words from a complete stranger made my birthday even better "

General Twitter Sentiment Wordcloud:

# Wordcloud of General Tweets
wordcloud (twitterOptimal, scale=c(5,0.5), max.words=200, random.order=F, 
           rot.per=0.35, use.r.layout=F, colors=brewer.pal(8, 'Dark2'))

Analysis of the General Twitter community:

As can be seen in the above 5 lines of general twitter sentiment, the accompanying wordcloud, and the above summary of word frequencies, random twitter comments tend towards expressing personal interests, and activities. Occasionally, popular Corporations are mentioned, although infrequently.

Analysis of Twitter Sentiment towards CVS:

As can be seen in the above 5 lines of CVS twitter sentiment, the accompanying wordcloud, and the above word frequency analysis, twitter comments about CVS tend towards informing Individuals in the Public about Employment opportunities at CVS. Less frequently mentioned are planned visits to CVS, and items that Individuals plan to buy at CVS.

3) Differentiating General Sentiment vs.CVS Sentiment

This section of the document attempts to determine whether the tweets coming from the Twitter community are different from the tweets from within the Company. A set of tweets are obtained from the Company's timeline, and combined with the random sample and the Public tweets (from parts 1 and 2). The entire set of tweets are then combined. Then, it is possible to identify if the clusters show that the Company tweets are different from the Public tweets.

# Tweets posted on the @CVS_Extra timeline
Qtimeline <- userTimeline('@CVS_Extra')
Qcontent <- do.call("rbind", lapply(Qtimeline, as.data.frame))

5 lines from @CVS_Extra Timeline:

Qcontent[1:5, 1]

wordcloud (as.character(Qcontent[,1]), scale=c(5,0.5), max.words=200, random.order=F, rot.per=0.35, use.r.layout=F, colors=brewer.pal(8, 'Dark2'))

Analysis of internal @CVS_Extra Twitter comments:

As can be seen in the above 5 lines of @CVS internal comments, the accompanying wordcloud, and the above word frequency analysis, @CVS internal comments tend towards resolving Customer inquiries, and verbally rewarding Customers for patronage of CVS.

Combination of General, CVS Public, CVS Timeline Wordcloud:

# Combine TheCompanyTimeline with GeneralTwitter and TheCompanyPublicTweets  
cloud <- c(Qcontent[1:100, 1], twitterOptimal[1:100], CVSOptimal)
wordcloud (cloud, scale=c(5,0.5), max.words=200, random.order=F, rot.per=0.35, use.r.layout=F, colors=brewer.pal(8, 'Dark2'))

Analysis of differences in Internal CVS twitter comments, and external twitter comments about CVS:

The above Wordcloud is a combination of general twitter comments, internal CVS twitter comments, and external twitter comments. Internal CVS phrases appear in the center of the wordcloud, and general twitter comments appear at the perimeter of the wordcloud. External twitter comments about CVS appear in an area between the center of the wordcloud, and the perimeter of the wordcloud.

This conclusively demonstrates the dramatic differences in key words used in general by the public, persons tweeting about CVS, and CVS social media managers.

Freq <- as.numeric(c(8, 7, 6, 4, 2, 80, 39, 26, 24, 15, 14))
Terms <- c("can", "info", "contact", "please", "team", "CVS", "job", "retail", "hiring", "shift", "supervisor")
Terms <- data.frame(Terms)
FreqTable <- cbind(Terms, Freq)
FreqTable <- data.frame(FreqTable)
ggplot(FreqTable, aes(x=reorder(FreqTable$Terms, -FreqTable$Freq), y=FreqTable$Freq)) +
geom_point() +
labs (x="Sentiment Word", y="Frequency",
title="CVS Timeline Comments vs CVS Twitter Sentiment")

4) Possible Problems with the Analytical Process

The creater of this document, (ContextBase), has a high level of assuredness in the reliability of the source data in portraying general Twitter comments, public Twitter comments about CVS, and comments posted to CVS timeline.

The general, random twitter comments are from a reliable corpora, ( available from http://www.corpora.heliohost.org. The same twitter corpora is also found at http://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/dsscapstone/dataset/Coursera-SwiftKey.zip).

5) Conclusions

As can be seen in the above analysis of CVS twitter sentiment, the accompanying wordclouds, and the word frequency analyses, twitter comments about CVS tend towards the interests of members of the public in obtaining employment at CVS. Other main interests in CVS, by the Public, includes planned visits, and obtaining needed items at CVS.
